<Layout title="What is Kelvin? Absolute Temperature Scale Explained" description="Understand the Kelvin temperature scale, why scientists use it, and how it relates to Celsius and Fahrenheit. Learn about absolute zero and its significance." keywords="kelvin temperature, absolute zero, kelvin scale, kelvin to celsius, temperature scales, SI temperature unit, scientific temperature">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Temperature</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">What is Kelvin? Absolute Temperature Scale Explained</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 22, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>You have probably heard of Celsius and Fahrenheit, but there is a third temperature scale used throughout science and engineering: Kelvin. Unlike the others, it starts at absolute zero — the coldest anything can theoretically get.</p>

      <h2>The Basics</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">0 K = -273.15°C = -459.67°F</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">K = °C + 273.15 (same degree size as Celsius, just shifted)</p>
      </div>
      <p>Kelvin uses the same increment size as Celsius — a 1-degree change in Celsius equals a 1-degree change in Kelvin. The only difference is where zero sits. Note: we write "300 K" not "300°K" — there is no degree symbol with Kelvin.</p>

      <h2>What is Absolute Zero?</h2>
      <p>Absolute zero (0 K) is the theoretical lowest temperature possible. At this point, atoms have minimal possible motion and cannot lose any more thermal energy. In practice, absolute zero can never be perfectly reached, but scientists have cooled materials to within billionths of a degree above it.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Absolute zero: 0 K = -273.15°C = -459.67°F</li>
        <li>Coldest lab temperature achieved: approximately 0.000000001 K</li>
        <li>Outer space (cosmic background): about 2.7 K (-270.45°C)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why Scientists Use Kelvin</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>No negative numbers:</strong> Temperature in Kelvin is always positive (or zero), which simplifies calculations</li>
        <li><strong>Direct proportionality:</strong> Gas laws (like PV = nRT) only work correctly with absolute temperature</li>
        <li><strong>Energy relationships:</strong> Doubling the Kelvin temperature doubles the thermal energy — this is not true with Celsius or Fahrenheit</li>
        <li><strong>SI standard:</strong> Kelvin is the official SI unit of thermodynamic temperature</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Everyday Temperatures in Kelvin</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Water freezes: 273.15 K (0°C / 32°F)</li>
        <li>Room temperature: 293-296 K (20-23°C / 68-73°F)</li>
        <li>Human body: 310 K (37°C / 98.6°F)</li>
        <li>Water boils: 373.15 K (100°C / 212°F)</li>
        <li>Light bulb filament: about 2,500 K</li>
        <li>Sun surface: about 5,778 K</li>
        <li>Sun core: about 15,000,000 K</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Kelvin in Everyday Life</h2>
      <p>You might encounter Kelvin more than you think:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Light bulb colour temperature:</strong> "2700K warm white" or "5000K daylight" on LED packaging</li>
        <li><strong>Photography white balance:</strong> cameras measure colour temperature in Kelvin</li>
        <li><strong>Astrophysics news:</strong> star temperatures are always reported in Kelvin</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
